description: From Middle English unsele, from Old English unsǣle, from Proto-Germanic *unsēliz, from *un- + *sēliz, equivalent to un- +‎ seel.

verbs.description: unseel (third-person singular simple present unseels, present participle unseeling, simple past and past participle unseeled)

entries.meaning: (obsolete) To open, as the eyes of a hawk that have been seeled.
(obsolete, by extension) To give light to; to enlighten.
